0.body: Calc: a fully-featured minimalistic calculator built in rust for educational purpose only.
0.title: Calc

1.body:
You can install the latest version from source git clone https://github.com/coco33920/calc
cd calc cargo build --release
./target/release/mini-calc or install it via cargo cargo install mini-calc
1.title: Install

10.body: you use it as a regular calculator
10.title: Usage

11.body: + for the addition - for the subtraction / for the division * for the multiplication ^ for the exponentiation
11.title: Basic Operators

12.body: It's easy to set a variable, just use myvar = value example: myvar = (2+2)
12.title: Setting variable

13.body: pi is pi as a double precision float e is e as a double precision float
13.title: Built-in variable

14.body: The following functions are available Trigonometry sin cos tan Hyperbolic trigonometry sinh cosh tanh Reverse trigonometry asin acos atan Exponentiation exp ln (alias: log) Vectors norm Matrices det invert Plot plot termplot Other sqrt factorial (aliases: fact or !) abs ceil floor round
14.title: Functions

15.body: For trigonometry, the input are assumed to be in radian, if not, you have to put "false" or "true" as second argument, example shown bellow img.png
15.title: Trigonometry

16.body: If you use the exp function you can pass a second argument for the base you are using, if no second arguments are passed this is assumed to be in natural base img.png
16.title: Exp/ln

17.body: You can take the nth root with the sqrt function, by default it takes the second root. img.png
17.title: Root

18.body: You can round to the nth decimal with the round function, by default it round to the integer (floor) img.png
18.title: Round

19.body: The language supports partial function img.png
19.title: Partial function

2.body: You can see how the calculator works over at the usage page
2.title: Usage

20.body: You can configure the general color, greeting message, greeting color, prompt and prompt color from the file for example in (for linux) ~/.config/mini-calc/mini-calc.toml Or situated in your operating system config folder.
20.title: Configuration

21.body: The default configuration looks like this img.png
21.breadcrumbs: Config » What the configuration looks like
21.title: What the configuration looks like

22.body: Available colors are purple cyan blue black red yellow green white an hexadecimal colour (ex: "#f7a8d8") Default colour (if the configuration fail to load) is Cyan.
22.title: Colors

23.body: Configuration: img.png It looks like: img.png
23.breadcrumbs: Config » Example of a modified configuration
23.title: Example of a modified configuration

24.body: You can interact and modify the config from the command line the commands are config: show the current config config reload: reload the config config reset: reset the config to default parameters config set categories are : greeting_message greeting_color prompt_color prompt general_color
24.breadcrumbs: Config » Interact in the command line
24.title: Interact in the command line

25.body: You can now use logic! I implemented the following functions: or (alias : ||) and (alias : &&) geq (alias : >=) gt (alias : >) leq (alias : <=) lt (alias :<) eq (alias : ==)
25.title: Logic

27.body: You can plot, backend is provided by GNUPlot, so it should work great on linux and macos but behiaviour on windows is not known.
27.title: Plot

28.body: To display the help just type help
28.title: Help
